blocks.value: Home-Based Rehabilitation Enhances Daily Physical Activity and Motor Skill in Children Who Have Undergone the Fontan Procedure

This randomized trial compared physical activity enhancing exercise prescription and education programs in 61 children (36 male) with single-ventricle physiology after Fontan. After Fontan, children are less active than recommended for optimal health. They are often geographically dispersed and unable to attend weekday programs. Participants, 5.9-11.7 years of age who were status 5.3 years post-Fontan, received 12-month, parent-delivered home programs to enhance physical activity, motor skill, fitness, and activity attitudes. Daily moderate-to-vigorous physical activity (MVPA) was measured at baseline and again at 6, 12, and months. Secondary outcomes were gross motor skill, fitness, and activity attitudes. Gross motor skill (p = .01) was significantly greater at the end of the 2-year study period for both intervention groups combined. MVPA at 2 years was significantly greater (p = .03) than the predicted decrease with age. Spring season (85 ± 25 min), male sex (69 ± 21 min), greater baseline activity (0.3 ± 0.1 min/baseline minute), and better gross motor skill (1.1 ± 0.4 min/percentile) increased weekly MVPA in a multivariable repeatedmeasures regression model adjusted for intervention, maturation during the 2-year study, sex, season, and baseline activity. Benefits were not influenced by type of rehabilitation, compliance, or rural/urban location. Home-based, pediatric physical activity rehabilitation enhances physical activity, gross motor skill, exercise capacity, and physical fitness among preadolescent children after Fontan regardless of rural/ urban location. Prescribed education and exercise programs are similarly effective for providing the important health benefits of daily physical activity. Enhanced gross motor skill is associated with increased MVPA despite exercise capacity limitations after Fontan. Rehabilitation attenuates the expected decrease in MVPA with age.

Cardiac rehabilitation includes exercise training, behavioral modification, psychosocial counseling, and risk-factor management. It is the standard of care for adult cardiac patients, although rural availability is limited. Cardiac rehabilitation for children with congenital heart defects is not well developed, although exercise training increases fitness during both the short and long terms.
Children with heart defects have sedentary lifestyles, a high prevalence of overweight beyond early childhood, and psychosocial challenges, suggesting that they would benefit from rehabilitation focused on physical activity behavior modification, healthy-lifestyle information, and psychosocial support. Complex heart defects are rare, which means that children are geographically dispersed. Unlike adult cardiac rehabilitation patients who are often retired or on leave from work, children's rehabilitation participation is dependent on parental availability and support. Effective rehabilitation for children with complex heart defects, in rural or urban locations, could be a template for all pediatric cardiac clinic patients.
This prospective, randomized comparison evaluated two rehabilitation models in preadolescent children with a functionally univentricular heart after Fontan. Both models focused on increasing physically active play, which has a significant role in childhood quality of life. We compared prescribed activity and education interventions using a parent-delivered format suitable for rural and urban locations. Both interventions prescribed specific daily activities to be performed. The activity intervention provided fitness and motor skill-development activities. The education program used play-based activities to build intrinsic motivation and develop the self-regulation skills needed to maintain greater physical activity levels after intervention. Educational activities were matched to the child/family's readiness fora change in the child's physical activity. We hypothesized that the education program would result in greater motivation and compliance during rehabilitation, which would be reflected in a slower decrease in postintervention physical activity. We also hypothesized that during the intervention, both programs would provide equal benefits for increasing daily physical activity, motor skill, and positive activity attitudes and perceptions.

Eligible children, 6-11 years of age, were at least 1 year post-Fontan. Study participation was approved by their cardiologist, who provided medically necessary activity restrictions (e.g., light to moderate intensity; no competitive sports; nobody contact; stay within comfortable limits; no isometric exercise [n = 3]; and no upside-down activities [n = 1]). Among children randomized to an intervention, 23 of 61 (38 %) were unrestricted in their physical activity. Children with disabilities that would limit full participation in the interventions were ineligible. The protocol complied with ethical standards and was approved by The Hospital for Sick Children Research Ethics Board (REB no. 100008413). Written informed parent consent and child assent were obtained.

Assessments, at community facilities or our pediatric hospital, were completed at baseline and again at 6 (midintervention), 12 (after intervention), and 24 months (1 year after intervention). Procedure details, outlined later in the text, have previously been reported. B.W.M., who was blind to study assessments and intervention delivery, used a random number generator within random blocks of two and four as well as sex strata to allocate participants to the activity prescription or education intervention. Randomization results were sealed in sequentially numbered opaque envelopes, opened after informed consent and baseline assessment were completed, by P.E.L. who enrolled participants and performed the interventions. Assessment staff did not have access to study group assignment.

Omni-directional accelerometers (Respironics Actical 2.1, Philips Healthcare, Andover, MA), worn at the midaxillary line above the iliac crest, measured moderateto-vigorous physical activity (MVPA) using 15-second epochs during all waking hours (5 schooldays and 2 nonschool days). Omni-directional accelerometers are expected to be more sensitive to movement outside of the vertical axis and have previously been validated for measuring physical activity in healthy children. The validity of the accelerometer measures in patients with congenital heart defects has been established. Our accelerometers were waterproof; thus, they could be worn during bathing and swimming. Minimum valid data were 3 schooldays and 1 nonschool day [39] each with at least 8 h of data. Unusual events (e.g., child illness), as well as any physical activities performed when the accelerometer was not worn (e.g., child unable to wear the accelerometer during karate competition) [39], were recorded on log sheets, thus allowing us to adjust the accelerometer data to more accurately reflect the physical activity performed.

Criterion-referenced scores assessed 6 locomotion and 6 object-manipulation motor skills (Test of Gross Motor Development-2, Pro-Ed, Austin, TX). Aerobic step test, grip strength, hamstring flexibility, and body mass index (BMI) assessed health-related fitness. Medical record reviews provided demographics and cardiac history. Heart rate (12-lead electrocardiogram; GE Medical Systems CASE 8000; Milwaukee, WI), blood pressure, oxygen consumption (Physiodyne MAX-2 metabolic cart, Quogue, NY), and respiratory quotient were assessed during two graded cardiopulmonary exercise tests (Bruce treadmill protocol and GE T-2000 treadmill, GE Healthcare, Waukesha, WI) at 0 and 12 months.

Activity attitudes were assessed through verbal administration of the Children's Self-Perception of Adequacy and Predilection for Physical Activity (CSAPPA) Scale. Specifically, we evaluated the activity adequacy and predilection subscores.

Both rehabilitation programs used a parent-lead, home/ community-based design to increase daily MVPA, improve motor skill and health-related fitness, and develop positive attitudes and self-efficacy for healthy, active lifestyles. The activities were specifically designed to encourage physically active play with friends and family (not competitive sports or activities with deliberate body contact) and were individually tailored to meet any activity restrictions specified by the participant's cardiologist. The intervention programs were designed to increase the child's daily MVPA through ''real world'' play-based activities that incorporated both static and dynamic exercise (e.g., Frisbee golf, beach ball volleyball, gymnastics). Programs were not designed to provide a fitness training effect, and did not specify exercise intensity. The play-based physical activity options allowed us to encourage abroad range of activity experiences while respecting any medically necessary activity restrictions.
Monthly, each family was sent specific written/ illustrated instructions for four 1-week sessions. Interventions required 1.5-2.0 h/week and were individualized to the child's interests, assessment results, and family resources. Each 1-week session included four different types of physical activity. Monthly programs continued for 1 year to encourage activity during all seasons. Mid-month contact obtained feedback and encouraged compliance. Parents rated program compliance for each of the preceding 6 months on a 15-cm visual analogue scale (0-100 %) at the 6-and 12-month assessments.

Education interventions suited the child's/family's readiness fora change in the child's MVPA. Educational activities (e.g., games, stories, Web sites) increased recognition of the need fora change in the child's activity participation, addressed ambivalence or concerns about participation, and encouraged a realistic plan for changing the child's activity level among families in the precontemplation, contemplation, or preparation stages of change, respectively. The goal was to move the child and family toward or into the action or maintenance stage so that the child's daily physical activity was increased. The education intervention was also designed to encourage selfdirected activity during and beyond the study as well as build intrinsic motivation for an active lifestyle. Families received healthy-lifestyle information, such as healthy eating, injury prevention, and activity benefits, in addition to the child's current activity level as measured by accelerometry. Puzzles conveyed activity rules and strategies; Web sites introduced skill and fitness progressions; and stories about active children who had previously undergone the Fontan procedure addressed anxiety, enhanced selfefficacy, and increased knowledge about appropriate activities. An example of 1 month of activities for the education intervention is provided in Appendix 1.

Specific exercises, physical activities, or skill-development activities were prescribed based on initial assessment results. At least 10 min of daily family and/or peer activity (e.g., walking, bike riding, skating) was included weekly. The goal was to directly increase the child's physical activity, fitness, and skill through prescribed activity sessions. An example of 1 month of activities for the activity intervention is provided in Appendix 2.

The MVPA value was the sum of all counts exceeding 400 per 15-second epoch. Wear time was calculated from parent logs. Total MVPA minutes/week were calculated [5 9 weekday average] ? [2 9 weekend average]. Baseline MVPA was normally distributed; thus, no data transformations were performed.
Gross motor skill and body composition results were converted to age-and sex-matched percentiles. Cardiopulmonary test z-scores were calculated from data for children with innocent murmurs. Flexibility and grip strength z-scores were calculated from data for Canadian children. Patient postal codes were used to categorize urban/rural location and estimate family income at a neighbourhood scale.

A sample size of 28 participants/arm provides sufficient power to identify an MVPA difference of 55 min/week (7.5 min/day was considered clinically relevant) based on a test for 2 means in a repeated-measures design of 4 time points. Summary statistics are described by the means ± SDs or frequencies. Repeated-measures linear regression analyses evaluated change during the 2-year study period. Variable selection was initially by study hypothesis and factors known to influence childhood physical activity (e.g., season of the year). Statistical significance was set at a = .05.
Participant age was the repeated-measures analysis time variable to adjust for maturation and time in study. Sex, season of the year, and baseline activity were obligatory variables due to their significant association with baseline activity. Racial/ethnic data were not available. Linear regression results are presented as estimates ± SEs. All analyses were performed using SAS software (version 9.2; SAS, Cary, NC).
Initially, the impact of the randomly allocated intervention on primary and secondary outcomes was examined. Outcome change during the 2-year study and influencing factors were then examined. Post hoc analyses, using stepwise forward variable selection, examined factors influencing rehabilitation benefits and participant physical activity relative to the internationally expected activity decrease with increasing age of 5-20 %/year. A sensitivity analysis compared results with and without participants who dropped out of the study to determine the difference in primary outcome between treatment arms.
The investigators had full access to the data and take responsibility for its integrity. Data for all subjects, within their randomly assigned group, were included in these analyses.

All post-Fontan children (n = 122) known to The Hospital for Sick Children were screened, and 110 children met the eligibility criteria. Seventy-two (69 %) children agreed to participate. Sixty-one children were randomized to an intervention (Fig.). Three children were not randomized because baseline MVPA results exceeded 90 min daily.

The 61 children (average age 9.1 years [quartile 1 (q1) = 7.7, quartile 3 (q3) = 10.5], 36 (59 %) male, 46 (75 %) urban]) randomized into the rehabilitation programs were 5.3 years (q1 = 4.2, q3 = 7.2) status post-Fontan (performed at an average of 2.9 years of age [q1 = 2.5, q3 = 3.8]). Cardiac diagnoses and histories were variable (Table), with most participants having an extracardiac Fontan (53 of 61) resulting in a functional single left (33 of 61 [54 %]) or right ventricle. Antithrombotic (38 of 61) and angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitor (28 of 61) medications were common, and the use of other medications and pacemaker was limited. Patient postal code indicated that 15 (23 %) children lived in rural areas and that family income was diverse (median = $73,884, q1 = $62,036, q3 = $87,607). Children (n = 33) who declined study participation were similar regarding sex (22 [67 %] male, p = .58), age (median 9.8 years [q1 = 7.6, q3 = 10.7, p = .51]), and rural/urban location (9 [39 %] rural, p = .55).
Fifty-seven (average age 9.1 years [q1 = 7.8, q3 = 10.5; 33 [58 %] male, 45 urban (79 %)] of the 61 children completed rehabilitation (n = 30 activity prescription) intervention, including 6-and 12-month assessments. Groups were comparable regarding all baseline measures (Table). Three families withdrew due to unrelated health problems (1 child and 2 parents). One family gave no reason for withdrawal. All withdrawals were from the education intervention. One year after rehabilitation, 54

Accounting for repeated measures and season, there was no significant difference in MVPA by treatment group at anytime point (p = .86). No difference by intervention was observed for any secondary outcome (gross motor skill, treadmill peak oxygen consumption, aerobic fitness score, grip strength, flexibility, BMI percentile, and child's selfreported adequacy and predilection for physical activity [Table]). Sensitivity analysis indicated no significant difference in results with or without withdrawn participants. Rural/urban location (p = .18) and parent-reported intervention compliance were not related to MVPA (p = .92).
Compliance was approximately 50 % for both interventions (activity intervention = % confidence limit [CL] 45 %, 56 %; education intervention = 95 % CL 31 %, 56 %; p = .27). After study completion, 40 (71 %) parents indicated that they would have chosen the activity-prescription group; 6 (11 %) parents indicated a preference for the education intervention; and 10 (18 %) parents had no preference. Some families reported that their children resisted the education program activities because they were ''schoolwork.'' Parents believed that the education program was a control intervention.

Our multivariable model of MVPA adjusted for rehabilitation program, repeated measures during the course of four study visits, age, sex, season, and baseline activity (Table). At 24 months, MVPA was 36 ± 31 min/week (p = .04) above baseline. Explanatory variables significantly associated with greater MVPA were better gross motor skill (1.1 min/week/ percentile, p = .01) and use of antithrombotic medication (67 min/week, p = .01). Weekly MVPA minutes were not associated with diagnosis (p = .29), left-or right-ventricle physiology (p = .55), years since Fontan completion (p = .76), or use of ACE-inhibitor medication (p = .31). Younger age at Fontan completion was associated with greater MVPA in a univariate analysis (18 ± 8 min/week/ year, p = .02) but not in the multivariable model.

Both rehabilitation programs improved age-and sexadjusted motor skill percentile scores, peak oxygen consumption by body weight, aerobic fitness, and flexibility (Table). Gross motor skill increased by 23 ± 5 percentiles (p \ .001) after rehabilitation, a 49 % improvement (Fig.). Motor skill percentiles increased with age (3.7 ± 1.1 percentile/year, p \ .01) and were greater for girls (19.7 ± 3.5, p \ .01). Motor skill was not influenced by rehabilitation program (p = .85), compliance (p = .19), season (p = .20), or rural/urban location (p = .36).

The 1-year postintervention total CSAPPA score was 59 ± 1.4 (p = .56). Subscores for adequacy (baseline = 20 ± 0.6, final = 21 ± 0.6, p = .51) and predilection (baseline = 27 ± 0.8, final = 28 ± 0.8, p = .68) were also unchanged. Given the 2-year study duration, a significant decrease in MVPA would be anticipated. Some researchers have suggested that the age-related decrease in physical activity begins as early as 3 years of age. Age and MVPA at baseline (361 ± 137 min/week) among our study participants, without adjustment for sex, showed a linear decrease of 21.9 min/year. The magnitude of this 7 % decrease is similar to or smaller than the decrease observed in healthy children, most probably because the initial activity levels were also lower. Measured MVPA was significantly greater than predicted, but not measured, values at 24 months (Table). Actual MVPA was greater than predicted, and the actual predicted difference was greater among female children and participants with lower baseline MVPA or better motor skills. A greater difference than predicted MVPA was also observed during the spring and fall (relative to winter) and among those taking antithrombotic medication.

Our study shows the feasibility and impact of pediatric cardiac rehabilitation emphasizing physical activity and healthy lifestyle behaviors among a cohort of children representative of the current era of Fontan palliation for functional single ventricle. Baseline exercise capacity and MVPA of participants were similar to previous reports. Both interventions enhanced health-related fitness and motor skill through a 1-year commitment to 2 activity h/week.  Weekly minutes of MVPA were constant in both groups throughout the 2-year study, attenuating the expected decrease in MVPA with increasing age. Initially it may seem counterintuitive that 1.5-2 h/week of play-based physical activity could significantly impact MVPA. However, we designed the play-based interventions to provide the child with options to engage in physical activity with family and friends, therefore enabling increased MVPA beyond the prescribed activities. Female participants and children who were less active at baseline obtained greater benefit from rehabilitation as indicated by a greater difference between predicted and measured MVPA.

Contrary to our hypothesis, both rehabilitation programs had similar compliance rates and rates of postintervention decrease. Parent views of the education intervention as a ''control group'' and children's perception of the puzzles and games as ''school work'' may have negatively impacted education-intervention compliance. Alternatively, the comparable compliance rates may reflect the motivation of families to comply with a cardiac rehabilitation program regardless of activity type or burden. Adult cardiac rehabilitation programs report 50 % compliance rates at 1 year. Our parent-reported compliance rates were similar for both rural and urban locations. Our homebased, parent-delivered design appears to yield comparable participation with much wider availability than approaches using a central facility. Our results confirm previous research that children with heart problems can improve their exercise capacity through prescribed physical activity and that benefits are maintained for 3 to 6 months. One previous study that implemented training within the immediate postoperative period found sustained benefits for 5 years. In contrast, our study promoted the broader benefits of physical activity and healthy lifestyles. None of the previous studies examined MVPA or motor skill. Our results demonstrate that activity and education interventions can provide the same fitness benefits with additional benefits for MVPA and gross motor skill. Our participants maintained MVPA during the 2-year study duration, which contrasts with the well-established decrease in daily physical activity with age.

Our study interventions enhanced motor skill by 49 %. At baseline, our results were consistent with published research showing ''low normal'' gross motor skills with gross and fine motor skill deficits for advanced skills. Our study participants significantly improved their gross motor skills, a change positively associated with daily MVPA. Activity attitudes are positively associated with MVPA and can predict future participation. A CSAPPA score C57 points is associated with sufficiently positive attitudes fora physically active lifestyle. Approximately 50 % of our participants had attitude scores lower than the recommended value, and there was no significant change during the study. Rhodes et al. found that exercise training increased children's belief that their activity participation had increased, but they did not report on participants' attitudes toward physical activity. Attitudes that are long-standing and important to the individual are difficult to change. Potentially, the study length was insufficient for significant attitude change. Gross motor skill improvements should, theoretically, translate into greater self-perceived adequacy for physical activity. Greater predilection scores would be expected among children who believe their participation will be successful. Greater MVPA levels relative to predicted values at 24 months suggest that predilection scores may continue to develop overtime. Regardless, changes in attitude appear unnecessary to increase physical activity in this population. Other potential mediators of behavior change, such as selfefficacy, as well as the benefits of additional counseling and support from a physical-activity professional, should be assessed in future studies.

Our study results are consistent with this theoretical pattern of behavior change alternating with regression to previous habits. Daily activity (MVPA) increased significantly by 6 months, decreased at 12 months, and then increased again. Fitness benefits were sustained throughout the intervention, and motor skill gains were maintained until 24 months. At 24 months, many parents reported that once their children did not ''have to'' do the intervention program, they initiated many of the study activities without prompting.
Participants' 1-year postintervention MVPA levels suggest the long-term benefits of a cardiac rehabilitation program for children with complex heart defects. Transient fitness changes are unlikely to impact long-term health because health benefits accrue from increased MVPA even in the absence physiological-fitness improvements. Childhood physical activity levels typically decrease with age. Although they were 2 years older after intervention, our participants were at or above their baseline level at the end of the study.

Participants were only children with the most complex form of congenital heart defect. Whether benefits would accrue to those with other pediatric heart problems has not yet been determined. All eligible children known to our clinic were approached for the study, but the MVPA and medical history of nonparticipants could not be assessed; thus, selection bias must be considered. It is unknown whether our participants represent the total population of children after Fontan, but 67 % of eligible children participated, and age and sex distribution were similar between participants and nonparticipants. Additional research is required to examine the benefits of cardiac rehabilitation for children who do not volunteer for an activity study.

Children after the Fontan procedure can successfully complete cardiac rehabilitation. Activity education and prescription are equally effective for maintaining MVPA and improving gross motor skill, exercise capacity, and fitness. The home-based, cardiac rehabilitation programs evaluated during this study enabled children from urban/ rural areas to benefit during the study period and up to 1 year after intervention.
